Sensor calibration is the process of adjusting a sensor's readings so that they match the actual physical values. It improves the accuracy and reliability of sensor measurements in an IoT system.

Why is it important?

Ensures accurate sensor readings.
Reduces measurement errors.
Improves the reliability of IoT applications and automation.
Calibration of an Analog Soil Moisture Sensor

To calibrate an analog soil moisture sensor, record two reference values:

Dry Soil Value: Measure the sensor output when the sensor is completely dry (e.g., 900).
Wet Soil Value: Measure the sensor output when the sensor is fully immersed in water or very wet soil (e.g., 300).

These two values are then used to convert any sensor reading into a moisture percentage (0%–100%).

Two-Point Calibration Method

The two-point calibration method uses two known reference points:

0% moisture (Dry soil)
100% moisture (Wet soil)

Any sensor reading between these two values is mapped to a percentage using the Arduino map() function or a similar calculation. This provides more accurate and meaningful soil moisture readings for IoT applications such as automatic irrigation systems.
